Exercise 1¶

1.1 Compute and sketch the solutions¶

We rewrite the solution of dynamical linear systems given in the lecture:

$\begin{aligned} \mathbf{x}(t) &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0\\ &=e^{Pt\Lambda P^{-1}}\mathbf{x}_0\\ &=Pe^{t \operatorname{diag}(\lambda_1, \ldots, \lambda_n)}P^{-1}\mathbf{x}_0\\ &=P\left(\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{\operatorname{diag}(t^n \lambda_1^n, \ldots t^n \lambda^n)}{n!}\right)P^{-1}\mathbf{x}_0\\ &=P\operatorname{diag}\left(\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{t^n \lambda_1^n}{n!}, \ldots \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{t^n \lambda_m^n}{n!}\right)P^{-1}\mathbf{x}_0\\ &=P\operatorname{diag}\left(e^{t\lambda_1}, \ldots e^{t \lambda_m}\right)P^{-1}\mathbf{x}_0\\ \end{aligned}$

Now we can calculate $e^{t\mathbf{A}} = P\operatorname{diag}\left(e^{t\lambda_1}, \ldots e^{t \lambda_m}\right)P^{-1}$:

In [345]:
A = sp.Matrix([[-0.5, -0.5, 0.], [-0.5, -0.5, 0.],[0.,0.,2.]])
P, L = A.diagonalize()
t = sp.Symbol('t')
etA = P.multiply((t*L).applyfunc(sp.exp)-sp.ones(3)+sp.eye(3)).multiply(P.inv())

In [253]:
# function to evaluate and plot x(t, x_0)
def x_tx0(tv, x0v):
    r = xt.evalf(subs={x0: x0v[0],
                       x1: x0v[1],
                       x2: x0v[2],
                       t: tv})
    return(np.array(r).astype(np.float64))
def plot(x0v, T=100, j=0):
    rs = []
    for i in range(T):
        rs.append(x_tx0(i, x0v))
    r = np.array(rs).squeeze()
    f= plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    ax=f.add_subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.plot(r[:,0], label=r'$x_1$')
    ax.plot(r[:,1], label=r'$x_2$')
    ax.plot(r[:,2], label=r'$x_3$')
    ax.set_xlabel("t")
    ax.set_ylabel("x(t)")
    ax.set_title(r"$x_{0,"+str(j)+"}$")
    sns.despine(offset=10, trim=True)
    plt.legend()

1.2 Compute the eigenvectors and the eigenvalues of $\mathbf{A}$¶

In [346]:
A = sp.Matrix([[-0.5, -0.5, 0.], [-0.5, -0.5, 0.],[0.,0.,2.]])
P, L = A.diagonalize()

The (not normalized) eigen vectors.

In [347]:
P
Out[347]:
$$\left[\begin{matrix}1.0 & -1.0 & 0\\1.0 & 1.0 & 0\\0 & 0 & 1.0\end{matrix}\right]$$

The eigen values

In [352]:
L[0,0], L[1,1], L[2,2]
Out[352]:
$$\left ( -1.0, \quad 0, \quad 2.0\right )$$

The first initial condition $\mathbf{x}_{0,1}=\left[\begin{array}{c}1\\1\\0\end{array}\right]$ only goes along the direction of the first eigen space related to the first eigen value which is negative. Therefore the fixed point is stable as shown in the plot.

The second initial condition $\mathbf{x}_{0,1}=\left[\begin{array}{c}1\\0\\0\end{array}\right]$ and third initial condition $\mathbf{x}_{0,1}=\left[\begin{array}{c}0\\1\\0\end{array}\right]$ are in in directions of the first and second eigen space. Since the first one is stable and the second one has eigen value 0 which is marginally stable the whole trajectory is stable.

The third initial condition $\mathbf{x}_{0,1}=\left[\begin{array}{c}0\\0\\1\end{array}\right]$ only goes along the direction of the third eigen space related to the third eigen value which is positive. Therefore the fixed point is unstable as shown in the plot.

1.5 Stationary solution for a constant input¶

We rewrite the solution of dynamical linear systems given in the lecture:

$\begin{aligned} \mathbf{x}(t) &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0 + \int_0^Te^{(t-t')\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{u}(t')dt'\\ &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0 + e^{tA}\int_0^te^{-t'\mathbf{A}}dt'\mathbf{u}\\ &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0 + e^{tA}\int_0^tP\operatorname{diag}\left(e^{-t'\lambda_1}, \ldots e^{-t' \lambda_m}\right)P^{-1}dt'\mathbf{u}\\ &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0 + e^{tA}P\operatorname{diag}\left(\int_0^te^{-t'\lambda_1}dt', \ldots \int_0^te^{-t' \lambda_m}dt'\right)P^{-1}\mathbf{u}\\ &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0 + e^{tA}P\operatorname{diag}\left(\left.-\frac{e^{-t'\lambda_1}}{\lambda_1}\right|_0^t, \ldots, \left.-\frac{e^{-t'\lambda_m}}{\lambda_m}\right|_0^t\right)P^{-1}\mathbf{u}\\ &= e^{t\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{x}_0 + e^{tA}P\operatorname{diag}\left(-\frac{e^{-t\lambda_1}}{\lambda_1}+\frac{1}{\lambda_1}, \ldots,-\frac{e^{-t\lambda_m}}{\lambda_m}+\frac{1}{\lambda_m}\right)P^{-1}\mathbf{u}\\ \end{aligned}$

In [293]:
A = sp.Matrix([[-0.5, -0.5, 0.], [-0.5, -0.5, 0.],[0.,0.,2.]])
P, L = A.diagonalize()
t = sp.Symbol('t')
etL = (t*L).applyfunc(sp.exp)-sp.ones(3)+sp.eye(3)
etA = P.multiply(etL).multiply(P.inv())
